Brief Hospital Course:
___ with a PMH of HIV/AIDS (CDR 59 in ___ with history of 
PCP), ESRD on HD MWF presented to the ED today complaining of 
chest pain which resolves w/percoset or maalox/lidocaine, now 
w/GPC bacteremia and fever to 103.  
.  
# CHEST PAIN
Patient originally presented with description of pleuritic 
substernal chest discomfort which was originally concerning for 
cardiac etiology but on further questioning her description was 
more suggestive of GI etiology including odynophagia-like 
symptoms and food intolerance. Full cardiac workup including EKG 
and serial cardiac enzymes was not suggestive of myocardial 
ischemia (troponins trended up but CKMB remained flat, so in 
this renal patient this was considered negative overall), and 
CTA was negative for PE or other pulmonary process. We 
considered pericarditis given her HIV+ status, but EKG showed no 
signs of pericarditis and pt was without pericardial friction 
rub or positional component. Patient underwent full GI workup 
with the support of the GI consult team, including upper GI 
barium series and EGD. These revealed only mild gastritis (for 
which she was started on omeprazole 20 BID) but no other 
pathology although we had considered candidal, CMV, or HSV 
esophagitis. She was maintained on mylanta/lidocaine cocktail 
q6H PRN in the hospital but this was stopped a few days prior to 
discharge given the aluminum content of mylanta, which is not 
compatible with her ESRD. Pain also resolved with percoset 
___, which she takes for diffuse myalgias/arthralgias (being 
worked up by neuro as an outpatient), so we suspect this is the 
underlying explanation for her symptoms at this time. 
.
#GPC BACTEREMIA
She spiked a fever to 102.7 on HD2, and blood cultures from that 
time grew coag-negative staph. Source thought to be her HD line. 
Started on vancomycin/cefepime initially; cefepime was stopped 
after 3d when cultures showed coag-neg staph. Subsequent 
surveillance blood cultures were negative or NGTD, but patient 
was persistently febrile, so the HD line was removed. 
.
# Retrocardiac opacity.  Two days prior to discharge, pt spiked 
at temperature.  She Infectious workup was done and only 
significant finding was a retrocardiac opacity on CXR.  She was 
started on cefepime.  Cultures remained negative and she did not 
spike a temperature.  Prior to discharge, repeat chest xray was 
performed and no evidence of opacity was noted, so abx treatment 
was discontinued.  
.
# HIV/AIDS 
Off HAART given non-compliance, outpatient ID specialist who is 
also her PCP (Dr ___ is aware. Patient noted to have 
recent low CD4 count of 59 and a high viral load, and hx PCP x3. 
ID consult team followed the patient, and recommended re-started 
HAART (as was done during other recent hospitalizations). 
Patient had compliance issues in the past due to other ongoing 
social stressors including secrecy about HIV diagnosis and 
housing challenges; we note that her motivation to take HAART is 
crucial to success. Patient saw social work throughout this 
admission, who recommended ongoing social work through Dr 
___ and also outreach to the ___. 
Patient did agree to resume both bactrim and azithromycin 
prophylaxis, which was done. 
.  
#CHRONIC PAIN SYNDROME/MYOSITIS/ARTHRITIS 
Patient known to have chronic migratory arthralgias and 
myalgias, is s/p thorough workup performed out-of-state within 
recent years per report. She has also recently started seeing a 
neurologist here at ___. On admission she was neurologically 
intact, with strength notable only for ___ strength in LEs. 
Unclear whether she suffers from inflammatory arthritis or 
osteoarthritis or chronic pain syndrome such as fibromyalgia. 
Her chronic pain syndrome could also explain the now-resolved 
episode of anterior chest wall pain without reproducible 
tenderness to palpation which prompted this admission. She will 
continue to see neurology as an outpatient, as already 
scheduled. 
.  
# ESRD/ACCESS
ESRD is chronic and secondary to HIV, on dialysis since ___ on 
___ schedule. Complicated by secondary hyperparathyroidism. When 
she was persistently febrile despite vancomycin coverage, the HD 
line was removed. This was done in the context of extensive 
discussion about the patient's difficult access and limited 
remaining access options (s/p three failed fistulas). At time of 
line removal, ID and renal consult teams (including outpatient 
nephrologist) were all aware and agreed line removal was 
necessary in order to fully treat her underlying bacteremia. She 
had a 2-day line holiday, and right sided groin temporary 
tunneled HD line was placed by interventional radiology and 
dialysis was resumed. She was continued on home selevamer, 
cinacalcet & started on daily nephrocaps. Received vitamin D and 
Epo supplementation at HD. She was also started on aspirin 81 mg 
QD. 
.
# Hx PCP ___: 
Has not been adherent to bactrim prophylaxis. This was restarted 
during this admission.
.  
# Hx Chronic Anemia: 
Hct at baseline during this admission without intervention. She 
was restarted on folic acid supplementation.
.  
# Hx Residual Right face zoster/post herpetic neuralgia: She 
does not have fresh/active lesions. She was continued on home 
percoset ___. 
. 
TRANSITIONAL ISSUES

INDICATION:  ___ woman febrile bacteremia on appropriate antibiotics
with left tunneled HD catheter removed over weekend for line holiday.  Needs
line replaced for hemodialysis ___.

COMPARISON:  CTA chest of ___.

OPERATORS:  Dr. ___ (resident), and ___
(attending interventional radiologist).  Dr. ___ was present throughout the
procedure.

SEDATION:  Conscious sedation with divided doses of intravenous fentanyl (100
mcg) and Versed (2 mg) over the total intraservice time of 1 hour and 15
minutes during which the patient's hemodynamic status was continuously
monitored by a trained radiology nurse.

CONTRAST:  Approximately 15 ml of Optiray 320 intravenous contrast.

PROCEDURE:  Informed consent was obtained from the patient after explaining
the benefits, risks, and alternatives to the procedure.  The patient was
placed supine on the imaging table in the interventional suite.  A
preprocedure timeout and huddle were performed per ___ protocol.

The left neck was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  Ultrasound
images demonstrated a patent left internal jugular vein.  Access was obtained
under ultrasound guidance.  A guidewire was placed through the access needle;
however, the wire could not be advanced beyond the central left subclavian
vein.  At this point, the needle was exchanged for a microsheath over the
guidewire.  Contrast was injected through the microsheath under fluoroscopic
guidance which demonstrated complete thrombosis of the central left subclavian
vein.

The right neck was then interrogated with ultrasound which demonstrated a
patent right internal jugular vein.  The right neck was prepped and draped in
the usual sterile manner.  Access was again obtained through the right
internal jugular vein under ultrasound guidance.  A guidewire was placed
through the needle and the needle was exchanged for a microsheath.  Contrast
was injected through the microsheath which demonstrated prominent collateral
veins; however, the right subclavian and SVC were not visualized.

After discussion with the patient's primary team including Dr. ___
and the nephrologist, Dr. ___, a decision was made to attempt a
tunneled femoral line the next day given the patient's continued low-grade
fevers.

IMPRESSION:  Unsuccessful attempt of placement of IJ HD catheter.  Venograms
demonstrated occlusion of the central left subclavian vein and also the right
subclavian.  Findings were discussed with Dr. ___ and Dr. ___
___ during the course of the procedure and at its end.  Recommendations for
MRV were made.

The patient is to come back tomorrow (___) for a tunneled femoral HD
catheter.

TUNNELED DIALYSIS LINE PLACEMENT

INDICATION:  ___ woman with febrile bacteremia, on antibiotics, left
tunneled hemodialysis line removed over the weekend for line holiday.

OPERATORS:  Drs. ___ (fellow), ___ (resident) and ___.
___ (attending physician).  Dr. ___ was present throughout the procedure.

SEDATION:  Moderate sedation with divided doses of intravenous ___ mcg
fentanyl and 4 mg of Versed over 70 minutes, during which patient's
hemodynamic status was continuously monitored by a trained radiology nurse.

CONTRAST:  None.

PROCEDURE:  Consent was obtained from the patient after explaining the
benefits, risks, and alternatives.  Timeout was performed as per ___
protocol.  The patient was placed supine on the imaging table in the
interventional suite.

Under aseptic conditions and sonographic guidance, a micropuncture needle was
placed in the right common femoral vein at the level of the midfemoral head. 
A 0.018 wire was advanced through the needle and into the IVC.  The needle was
exchanged over the wire for 4.5 ___ microsheath.  Inner cannula and wire
were removed to facilitate placement of a 0.035 ___ wire, which was advanced
into the right atrium.  Appropriate measurements were made.  Attention was
directed to the right anterior thigh at an appropriate distance from the
venotomy site.  Skin was infiltrated with adequate amounts of 1% lidocaine.  A
small skin incision was made.  The proposed tunnel site was subcutaneously
infiltrated with a mixture of 1% lidocaine and epinephrine.  A new 15.5 ___
50-cm (tip-to-cuff) hemodialysis catheter was connected to a blunt metallic
dissector and tunneled subcutaneously from the skin incision site to exit at
the puncture site overlying venotomy.  Microsheath was removed to perform
serial dilatation with 8, 12 and 14 ___ dilators under fluoroscopy,
eventually leading to placement of a 16 ___ peel-away sheath.  The wire and
inner dilator were removed to facilitate placement of the tunneled catheter. 
Sheath was peeled away.  Catheter tip was confirmed under fluoroscopy to be in
the right atrium.  Catheter was secured by 0 silk sutures.  Puncture site was
sutured with subcuticular ___ Vicryl suture.  Sites were appropriately
dressed.  The patient tolerated the procedure.  No immediate post-procedural
complications were seen.

IMPRESSION:  Uncomplicated placement of a 15.5 ___ 50-cm (tip-to-cuff)
tunneled hemodialysis catheter via the right common femoral vein with its tip
in the right atrium.  The catheter is ready for use.

HISTORY:  ___ female with HIV and fever.  Evaluation for pulmonary
